1
00:00:03,344 --> 00:00:06,480
Сreation
is a secondary function

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:10,969
performed by a part of a part
of a part of His expansion,

3
00:00:10,969 --> 00:00:14,391
with His eyes half-closed.

4
00:00:14,786 --> 00:00:16,255
Like we say in this world

5
00:00:16,255 --> 00:00:17,799
when people think they’re
[good at] something,

6
00:00:17,799 --> 00:00:20,242
they go, “I can do that
with my eyes closed.”

7
00:00:20,242 --> 00:00:22,387
“Yes, you can do that
with your eyes closed.”

8
00:00:22,540 --> 00:00:24,774
[Kṛṣṇa Over Viṣṇu]

9
00:00:25,189 --> 00:00:27,453
But it’s generally an expression,

10
00:00:27,453 --> 00:00:30,064
“I can do this 
with my eyes closed.”

11
00:00:30,064 --> 00:00:33,146
You can do those kind of things
or maybe not.

12
00:00:33,299 --> 00:00:36,853
Mahāviṣṇu generates
innumerable universes

13
00:00:36,853 --> 00:00:41,895
out of His pores 
with His eyes half-closed; half-asleep.

14
00:00:41,895 --> 00:00:45,424
He’s lying in yoga-nidrā

15
00:00:45,424 --> 00:00:49,322
with His eyes half-closed, 
half-asleep,

16
00:00:49,337 --> 00:00:53,673
and His glance is personified
as Śambhu Śiva,

17
00:00:53,673 --> 00:00:55,594
full of the sum total of jīvas,

18
00:00:55,594 --> 00:00:58,706
and they’re impregnated
in the material nature

19
00:00:58,706 --> 00:01:01,752
while He’s doing this: [exhales]

20
00:01:02,368 --> 00:01:05,214
So in His outward going breath,

21
00:01:05,214 --> 00:01:09,097
a hundred and fifty-trillion years,

22
00:01:09,112 --> 00:01:11,194
innumerable universes appear.

23
00:01:11,194 --> 00:01:13,261
He can do it 
with His eyes closed

24
00:01:13,261 --> 00:01:21,485
while Kṛṣṇa’s playing with the gopas
and gopīs in Vṛndāvan.

25
00:01:21,485 --> 00:01:23,613
That’s beauty over power.

26
00:01:23,613 --> 00:01:26,727
There are many examples
of beauty over power:

27
00:01:26,727 --> 00:01:31,519
Kṛṣṇa over Rāmachandra;
Kṛṣṇa over Viṣṇu.

28
00:01:33,210 --> 00:01:38,249
The ultimate conception of
the ultimate reality is beauty,

29
00:01:38,249 --> 00:01:39,611
and as Guru Mahārāj says,

30
00:01:39,611 --> 00:01:42,975
“Beauty is the ultimate
controlling principle.”

31
00:01:42,975 --> 00:01:49,191
So, Mahāviṣṇu steals that brāhmaṇ’s boy.
Why?

32
00:01:49,191 --> 00:01:53,461
We find out in the Bhāgavatam.

33
00:01:53,461 --> 00:01:58,340
He wants to see
the beauty of Kṛṣṇa.

34
00:01:58,340 --> 00:01:59,942
How to get Kṛṣṇa to come?

35
00:01:59,942 --> 00:02:03,592
He stole the boy
and He’s keeping him there.

36
00:02:03,592 --> 00:02:05,822
… such a cruel thing to do.

37
00:02:05,822 --> 00:02:09,191
And Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna go through
all the layers of the Universe

38
00:02:09,191 --> 00:02:13,969
and then He says, “I just wanted
to see Your beauty, my Lord.”

39
00:02:13,969 --> 00:02:16,808
Should we think Viṣṇu 
is not beautiful?

40
00:02:16,808 --> 00:02:19,380
Inconceivably beautiful.

41
00:02:19,671 --> 00:02:23,875
But what was the śloka 
of the day?

42
00:02:24,168 --> 00:02:27,291
sarvādbhuta-chamatkāra-
līlā-kallola-vāridhiḥ

43
00:02:27,291 --> 00:02:32,558
atulya-madhura-prema-
maṇḍita-priya-maṇḍalaḥ

44
00:02:32,558 --> 00:02:38,841
trijagan-mānasākarṣi-
muralī-kala-kūjitaḥ (Cc: Madhya, 23.82-83).

45
00:02:38,841 --> 00:02:41,960
Kūjitaḥ means
it sounds very beautiful.

46
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:44,592
Muralī, Kṛṣṇa’s flute.

47
00:02:44,592 --> 00:02:56,131
Muralī-kala-kūjitaḥ
asamānordhva-rūpa-śrī:

48
00:02:56,386 --> 00:02:58,503
No one equals His beauty,

49
00:02:58,503 --> 00:03:02,725
not Viṣṇu, not Rāma,
not Dvārakā-Kṛṣṇa.

50
00:03:04,363 --> 00:03:08,303
Dvārakā-Kṛṣṇa sees the picture
and says,

51
00:03:08,303 --> 00:03:12,738
“I was so beautiful
when I was younger in Vṛndāvan.”

52
00:03:12,738 --> 00:03:14,861
Like in this world.

53
00:03:16,261 --> 00:03:20,264
My cousin, who’s my age,
she told my mom

54
00:03:20,281 --> 00:03:22,577
—now I won’t say her age,

55
00:03:22,577 --> 00:03:24,542
because somehow over the years

56
00:03:24,542 --> 00:03:27,074
there are like 
ten years separating us,

57
00:03:27,074 --> 00:03:30,406
even though we were born
in the same year.

58
00:03:32,434 --> 00:03:36,836
Anyway, 
and my mom is ninety-three,

59
00:03:36,836 --> 00:03:39,927
she doesn’t mind me 
saying that.

60
00:03:40,066 --> 00:03:42,197
My cousin said to her,

61
00:03:42,197 --> 00:03:47,883
“Aunt Rose, let’s look at some pictures
when we used to look good,

62
00:03:47,883 --> 00:03:50,128
when we used to be beautiful.”

63
00:03:50,128 --> 00:03:54,170
So, Kṛṣṇa also has
a version of that.

64
00:03:54,170 --> 00:03:57,251
He’s saying, “Oh, I was so beautiful
in Vṛndāvan.

65
00:03:57,251 --> 00:03:59,579
Now these days,

66
00:03:59,579 --> 00:04:02,783
maybe I put on a little weight
in Dvārakā.

67
00:04:02,783 --> 00:04:05,293
It’s hard to say.”

68
00:04:06,281 --> 00:04:11,407
Or He sees His own beauty
in a jewelled column and says,

69
00:04:11,416 --> 00:04:14,778
“Who is so beautiful that now
I’m starting to feel

70
00:04:14,778 --> 00:04:18,659
the same feelings as Rādhikā.”

71
00:04:20,012 --> 00:04:25,823
So, even Kṛṣṇa is enamoured
by His own beauty,

72
00:04:25,885 --> 00:04:28,730
asamānordhva-rūpa-śrī (Cc: Madhya, 2.23.82-83),

73
00:04:28,730 --> 00:04:32,638
the rūpa. Rūpa means form,
and rūpa means beauty.

74
00:04:32,638 --> 00:04:34,831
Rūpa śrī, śrī rūpa.

